column69: Potentiostat with a rotating disk electrode
column70:
The University is intending to purchase a Potentiostat with a rotating disk electrode.

The GEIC equipment fund is part financed by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) funds having been awarded under the 2014-2020 Priority Axis 1: Promoting Research and Innovation.

The equipment is being purchased for the Graphene Engineering and Innovation Centre ("GEIC") at the University of Manchester.  The GEIC is a £60 million investment which will establish a state of the art research and technology development facility for graphene and related 2D materials.  Projects in the GEIC will be industry-led and will focus on innovation and applications, with the aim of accelerating research through to products in the marketplace. The GEIC will house pilot production facilities and characterisation equipment. It will initially focus on a number of the University's world-class graphene application areas: energy, composites, formulations and coatings, electronics and membranes.

Given the world leading graphene research at the University, it is expected that all the equipment in the GEIC will be cited in high profile academic publications as well as underpinning industrial collaboration projects, thus giving the equipment a high degree of exposure.
The GEIC will be situated on the North Campus of The University of Manchester, comprise of ~8400 m2 and has been designed by world-renowned architect Rafael Viñoly. It is set to be open in summer 2018. Equipment purchased before the GEIC building is opened will be temporally commissioned elsewhere in the University campus, typically in the National Graphene Institute, and then moved into the GEIC once it is completed.

For further information on the GEIC please see: 
http://www.graphene.manchester.ac.uk/collaborate/geic/

column69: Brooklands Museum - Exhibition Fit Out Contractor
column70:
Brooklands Museum is inviting tenders from experienced Exhibition Fit Out Contractors for its major new project, the Brooklands Aircraft Factory and Race Track Revival project.
The project which will see the creation of a new Aircraft Factory visitor experience in the Museum's conserved World War 2 Bellman Hangar. The exhibition will have a very strong emphasis on authenticity and interactivity and will showcase aircraft, aircraft components and other objects from the Museum's collection.
The project also includes the erection of a two storey Flight Shed to house the Museum's live aircraft and associated exhibition elements. In addition, the iconic Finishing Straight of the iconic Brooklands race track will be reinstated and new exhibition elements will give visitors a sense of the race track in its heyday.
The scope of the appointment covers exhibition fit out including setworks, metalwork, specialist joinery, graphics production, mounts (incl mannequins), second fix exhibition-specific M&E, showcases, lighting, AV hardware installation.  Separate contracts have, or will be, let for mechanical interactives, AV software/media and illustration.
The Exhibition Designer for the project is Ralph Appelbaum Associates, the Project Manager is Focus Consultants and the Quantity Surveyor is IKS Consulting.
The Aircraft Factory Experience, Flight Shed and Finishing Straight are due to open in summer 2017 and the exhibition must be installed, tested and snagged in time for the opening.
All Invitation to Tender documentation can be downloaded from the following link: https://www.dropbox.com/sh/fcvy663brb6mern/AABxO9EHaebsCref9QXDg3w-a?dl=0

column70: The International Music and Performing Arts Charitable Trust, a registered charity, number SC046904, and known as IMPACT Scotland, is planning a new Medium-sized concert hall (approx. 1000 seats) in the heart of Edinburgh's World Heritage Site.  It will be home to the Scottish Chamber Orchestra and used as a venue by the Edinburgh International Festival (EIF).  As a venue, worthy of calling home to the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, it must have an acoustic to rival any other classical venue in the world. It must also be robust enough to adapt to and serve the many and varied performers at the EIF and attract visiting performing art groups, both local and international.  The total estimated cost of the new concert hall is currently c.GBP40m.IMPACT Scotland is seeking to appoint a design team to provide a full scope of design services corresponding to RIBA stages 1-7.  This procurement is not a competition to identify and deliver that design, rather to identify and appoint a design team.

Via a Further Competition against CCS Framework RM3733 Technology Products 2, Lot 2, University Hospitals Bristol NHS Foundation Trust is seeking to procure a secure collaboration and file sharing solution. The solution must be compatible with the Trusts existing file system, Active Directory, and will securely allow users to share data and collaborate with colleagues and peer groups who are employed by the Trust or work for partner organisations.

The functionality must include secure file transfer, file sharing, file synchronization, mobile application provision, an online viewer and a single sign on facility.

The proposal must offer an on premise or UK hosted solution that could be used by other health and social care partners to manage and offer the same service but who are not part of the Trusts active directory domain.

This is only open to suppliers on the CCS Framework RM3733 Technology Products 2, Lot 2.

column69: Cambridgeshire County Council Request for quotation for drafting Education, Health & Care Plans
column70:
Cambridgeshire County Council [The Council] seek to purchase services for the drafting of Education, Health & Care Plans (EHCPs) following a transfer review (for those children and young people who have previously had a Statement of SEN). 

The Council require 300 reviews in total to be drafted as EHCPs; 134 within the first 6 weeks of contract, and the remaining 166 within the following 6 weeks.

Via a Further Competition against CCS Framework RM3733 Technology Products 2, Lot 2, University Hospitals Bristol NHS Foundation Trust is seeking to procure a operational intelligence and performance solution to enable the Trust to be more agile and proactive, that will provide real-time operational intelligence for its complex dynamic production environment.

The chosen solution will assist the Trust with IT planning and decision making whilst improving collaboration among teams and decreasing its dependence on domain experts to triage issues.

It is envisaged the solution will receive unstructured network traffic and then perform real-time full stream reassembly to extract application level protocol information, in order to monitor the performance of applications running on the Trusts network and detect abnormal behaviour that could indicate a data breach.

This is only open to suppliers on the CCS Framework RM3733 Technology Products 2, Lot 2.

The scope of the agreement shall cover the XRD system but not any peripheral equipment, though the Potential provider shall be capable of supporting peripheral equipment if required and as an optional extra to the basic cover.
It is likely that the Authority will have an ad-hoc requirement for staff to be trained in the use the system. The contract shall therefore include the provision for expert advice and training to be arranged if required and separately to the maintenance and support agreement.
The support contract shall include:
Two (2) routine maintenance visits per annum (February and August)
The replacement of parts and consumables associated with the completion of
the routine maintenance visits (spares kit)
Breakdown labour
Telephone support

The mandate of the European Spallation Source ERIC
is to design, plan, construct, commission, operate and
decommission the European Spallation Source (ESS).
It is located in Lund, Sweden, co-hosted by Sweden
and Denmark and has more than 17 Partner
Countries, including the UK. The UK contribution is
coordinated by STFC. The facility will deliver its first
neutrons in 2019 and is expected to be fully
operational by 2025.
The European Spallation Source (ESS) will be one of
the largest infrastructures in Europe and will be used
for neutron production for materials research. It will
use a long pulsed superconducting linac and
accelerate a 62.5 mA proton beam current to the
energy of 2000 MeV. Peak beam power to the target
will be 125 MW, 7 times more than the highest power
existing facility.STFC are providing a number of goods
and services on behalf of the ESS. This tender is for
components of the RF distribution system (RFDS) for
the Spoke, Medium beta elliptical and High beta
elliptical cavities.

We are seeking to commission a sustainable health and education programme which helps transform school meals and food education in schools and their communities. The aim is to give school pupils and their families the confidence, skills and knowledge they need to cook, grow and enjoy good quality, affordable food, as well as increasing their understanding of where their food comes from. The programme should use food as a way to engage the community and improve the whole school experience, making lunchtimes a positive feature of the day and enriching classroom learning with farm visits and practical cooking and growing. Ultimately the aim of the programme is to give schools the tools they need to make long term changes to their food culture and their curriculum to support healthy behaviours.  The programme will be available to every school in Leicestershire, but with the main focus on  primary and Special (SEN) schools. The Programme will work in partnership with the County Council and Public Health team to deliver this programme as part of the Leicestershire Healthy Schools Programme. The contract is being offered for an initial period of 12 months, with the option to extend for up to a further 24 months.

Additional information: Tender documents available to download from www.eastmidstenders.org

column69: Smart Oxford Competition - Project Management and Delivery
column70:
A supplier is being sought who will project plan, manage and deliver the Smart Oxford Competition and work alongside the winning entry (or entries) to successfully deliver the project in Oxford.  Support and oversight will be provided by the Smart Oxford Project Board.

Oxford City Council, on behalf of the Smart Oxford Project Board, is leading on the delivery of a flagship project that raises Smart Oxford's profile and helps people understand the opportunities and benefits that can be achieved through the Internet of Things (IoT) and the use of technology, data and communities - a project that catches the imagination of all who live, visit and work in and around the city.  

We have decided to run a competition to find a project that engages with all communities in Oxford.  Projects that enter must be fun; interactive; informative; accessible to all; creative; sustainable; relevant and impactful; smart and innovative.  

We want to capture people's imaginations and get people talking through a fun and learning experience that helps people understand the opportunities and benefits that can be achieved through Smart Oxford, IoT and the use of technology, data and communities.  We want there to be a legacy through either the project itself or through the principles of the competition and winning project.

column68: North West Non-Emergency Patient Transport Service
column69: North West Non-Emergency Patient Transport Service
column70:
The existing five non-emergency patient transport service (PTS) contracts in the North West (NW) region are expired on 30th June 2016.
NHS Blackpool CCG Ambulance Commissioning is co-ordinating the re-commissioning of these services, on behalf of the 33 NW CCGs. NHS Shared Business Services (NHS SBS) is an agent of the Lead Commissioner, and are acting on their behalf to carry out the Procurement of the Service. This exercise will took place under an open, fair and transparent procurement process, designed to allow all potential providers or consortia, the opportunity to demonstrate approaches by which they would deliver safe, reliable and cost-effective patient transport services to eligible patients in the North West. The eligibility of patients for this service is determined by the Department of Health Eligibility Criteria.

Additional information: The key strategic objectives of the procurement and subsequent service to be delivered were to:
• Satisfy CCG's responsibility for the provision of suitable transport for eligible patients
• Ensure patients equity of access to healthcare
• Deliver measureable improvements in patient experience
• Obtain best value for money
PTS comprises the movement of patients whose condition is not considered an 'emergency' between patients' homes, hospitals, community settings or other treatment centres, for people referred for consultations, treatments or procedures. This can and should encompass a wide range of vehicle types and levels of care consistent with the patients' medical need(s).
The procurement was split into the 5 Lots for each of the Commissioners and Bidders were able to bid for 1,2,3,4 or all 5 Lots. The Lots are as detailed below: 
• Lot 1 - Patient Transport Service for NHS Cumbria 
• Lot 2 - Patient Transport Service for NHS Lancashire
• Lot 3 - Patient Transport Service for NHS Cheshire, Warrington and Wirral
• Lot 4 - Patient Transport Service for NHS Merseyside 
• Lot 5 - Patient Transport Service for NHS Greater Manchester

column70:
This contract will study the construction of 'Low Cost, Low Carbon' housing developments in order to understand:
- The drivers, barriers, attitudes and challenges through the various stages of construction, from specification and design, through construction and supply chain, to hand-over and occupancy. 
- The costs and cost drivers associated with construction.
- The actual energy performance of these homes when occupied and the reasons behind this performance.

The evidence will be used to support the case for policy to support low-carbon building construction and an understanding of the art of the possible to inform future emissions reductions plans. Evidence will be collected primarily through social research, site inspections and home energy monitoring.

Additional information: Please contact research@uksbs.co.uk to register your interest for details relating to a planned supplier day to be held on 13th January 2017.

The current service provider is the College of Social Work (TCSW); which will close by the 30th September 2015. The Department is seeking to protect its previous investment by ensuring that Government funded programmes and products currently provided by TCSW remain available to the Social Work sector.  This tender is for provision of four specific services and the period of the Contract is two years, with a potential extension of a further one year. 
The services are:
•	Hosting on a website various publications that were commissioned by Government;
•	Hosting the Principal Social Worker (PSW) Network (Adults);
•	Hosting the Principal Social Worker Network (PSW) (Children’s); and
•	Certification of the Assessed and Supported Year in Employment (ASYE) (adults).
This is notification that the Department is running an accelerated Ojeu Open Procurement for the services described. – (for which see ITT ref number 59955).
Interested suppliers need to register on the BMS system if they have not done so already. details of registration can be found on the attached document and link provided.

Interested suppliers must read the attached Invitation to Tender documents carefully and respond by the deadline 07/09/2015 – by 14:00:00. All responses must be in English Language and submitted via the BMS e-tendering portal before the deadline shown for receipt of ITTs. Late responses will not be accepted. Information on registration can be found at- https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-of-health/about/procurement. Organisations wishing to be considered for this contract must register their intent to participate through this system. Registration is a simple one-step process; the supplier must register as a company/organisation; then each employee who may undertake a tendering exercise must then register as an individual. Once this stage is completed, it is then possible to register expression of interest for this tender. column69: Framework Agreement for the Provision of Construction Work 2017 - 2021
column70:
The objective of this tender process is to establish a framework agreement to provide construction works to Wigan Council. The majority of the construction works to be undertaken will relate to school and educational buildings. The duration of the framework agreement will be 4 years. The framework will be split into 2 lots. Lot 1 will meet individual project requirements ranging in cost from 250 000 GBP to 1 000 000 GBP and Lot 2 in the cost range > 1 000 000 GBP to 5 000 000 GBP. All contractors appointed to the framework agreement must be able to undertake projects to the upper project cost limit within the lot tendered for. It is intended to award places on each lot of the framework agreement to 8 contractors. Interested contractors will be able to apply for one or both lots. The anticipated total financial value of works to be put through the framework agreement over the duration of the framework is estimated to be in the region of 50 000 000 GBP, however this will be dependent on funds made available through Wigan Council's capital investment programme. Wigan Council does not guarantee any volumes or specific values of work to be placed under the framework. Individual contracts raised under the framework agreement can commence at any time after the commencement date of the framework. The construction work will be predominantly school build works however Wigan Council reserves the right to use the framework for other more general requirements when necessary. There will be potential for partner organisations or other areas of the Council to use the framework e.g. academies, the diocese, WLCT.

Each requirement for work identified requiring use of the framework will be tendered to all the suitable framework contractors in the form of mini competitions. The time limit set for responses will vary, but will take into account the complexity of requirements and time needed to prepare and submit responses in each case. Mini Competitions will include work based on a Project Partnering arrangement and/or Traditional tendering basis. The conditions of contract relevant to projects tendered under the terms of the framework shall be either a Standard Form of Partnering Agreement (PPC2000 ACA or similar) or a Standard JCT Form of Building Contract.

The closing date and time for the receipt of final tender applications is 17th January 2017 at 12:00 noon. 

The procurement documents are available for unrestricted and full direct access, free of charge, at https://www.the-chest.org.uk ('The Chest' North-West E-Procurement Portal).

This Contract Notice was submitted for publication in the Official Journal of the European Union (OJEU) on 29th November 2016 and published with reference number 2016/S 233-423870.

Additional information: Wigan Council is using the e-procurement portal known as The Chest at https://www.the-chest.org.uk/ to conduct the procurement exercise. To gain access to the tender documents applicants will need to register their details at the following link https://procontract.due-north.com/register. Once registered applicants will be e-mailed a log-in and password which will allow them to gain access to the tender documents.

column69: GP Clinical Support for Intermediate Care Facilities
column70:
The Council and CCG are investing in two new bed-based intermediate care facilities, including 10 reablement beds in Protheroe House and four nursing beds Priscilla Wakefield. This scheme will be piloted for 12 months and aims to provide short term intensive support, to aid recovery and independence, following illness, injury or some other issue that has prevented them returning or remaining home. The goal is to provide people with the best possible opportunity to return home, live independently and avoid unnecessary long-term residential care packages. 
The service will be supported by a multi-disciplinary team, which will support all 14 beds. This team will contain the following skill mix: 
•	GP
•	Team manager
•	Social Worker
•	Occupational Therapist
•	Physiotherapist
•	Rehabilitation assistant
•	Nurse
•	Pharmacist
•	Reablement workers and managers (based at Protheroe House)
•	Nurses and managers (based at Pricilla Wakefield)
For this pilot, the MDT will be provided by Whittington Health, with the exception of the Social Worker (provided by Haringey Council) and the GP (provided through this arrangement).
This services specification is designed to secure GP leadership for the multi-disciplinary team along with GP registration and care coordination for each patient.

Additional information: Please note deadline is 12 noon on 14/12/2016

Deadline has been extended to this date from the previous deadline of 09/12/2016

        and search for the notice with reference 'UK-BRISTOL: Engineering design services.'.

The University has chosen to purchase a Thermobalance (thermogravimetric analyzer).

The GEIC equipment fund is part financed by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) funds having been awarded under the 2014-2020 Priority Axis 1: Promoting Research and Innovation.

The equipment is being purchased for the Graphene Engineering and Innovation Centre ("GEIC") at the University of Manchester.  The GEIC is a £60 million investment which will establish a state of the art research and technology development facility for graphene and related 2D materials.  Projects in the GEIC will be industry-led and will focus on innovation and applications, with the aim of accelerating research through to products in the marketplace. The GEIC will house pilot production facilities and characterisation equipment. It will initially focus on a number of the University's world-class graphene application areas: energy, composites, formulations and coatings, electronics and membranes.

Given the world leading graphene research at the University, it is expected that all the equipment in the GEIC will be cited in high profile academic publications as well as underpinning industrial collaboration projects, thus giving the equipment a high degree of exposure.
The GEIC will be situated on the North Campus of The University of Manchester, comprise of ~8400 m2 and has been designed by world-renowned architect Rafael Viñoly. It is set to be open in summer 2018. Equipment purchased before the GEIC building is opened will be temporally commissioned elsewhere in the University campus, typically in the National Graphene Institute, and then moved into the GEIC once it is completed.

For further information on the GEIC please see: 
http://www.graphene.manchester.ac.uk/collaborate/geic/

column69: Reseach for OPCC on HBA, FGM, FM
column70:
The OPCC for Hertfordshire wishes to commission an academic institution by tender process to conduct the research and analysis and produce recommendations that will form the commissioning intentions for services for victims of HBA, FM & FGM as well as to meet the aims and objectives set in the Police and Crime Plan and County Domestic Abuse Strategy.This will be a one off research project led by the OPCC and the HBA subgroup in partnership with the supplier body. This research will involve statutory and non-statutory agencies including Hertfordshire Constabulary, Independent Domestic Violence Advocates (IDVAs), HCJB, Crown Prosecution Service, Her Majesty's Courts and Tribunal Service, Victim Support and Witness Care Units. 
The aim of this project is to gather evidence from victims, stakeholders and wider research to help the OPCC develop a service specification for victims of HBA, FM and FGM that will assist in the commissioning of victim services in Beacon. The research will include primary and secondary research, review and mapping of current national and local guidance to the victims' code of practice, practitioner and victim interviews and contact with service providers and interested groups.
